When a small group of animals (minorally small) separate from the main population from which they originate (for example, when they cross a mountain ridge or river or move to a new island from which it is not easy to get back), they often find themselves in a different environment than they were before.
This new environment has different sources and different competitors, so the new population will need different qualities or ways of adaptation to become a stronger competitor than in the past.
The original population has not changed at all, they still need the same adaptations as before.
Over time, as the new population adapts to its new environment, they begin to look less and less like the rest of the population.
Finally, for several thousand or even millions of years, these two populations will be so different that they will no longer be considered the same species.
This process is called speciation, which means the emergence of new species. Specialization is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
